        <!-- Section 30: General Cleaning Techniques (Part 1) -->
        <div id="section30" class="section">
            <h2>General Cleaning Techniques</h2>
            <p>1. Start with "dry before wet."</p>
            <p>Begin by removing loose dirt and debris with dry methods like sweeping, vacuuming, or dusting. Only then move to wet cleaning (e.g., mopping or wiping) to avoid turning dust into muddy streaks.</p>
            <p>2. Work from top to bottom.</p>
            <p>Clean high areas first—ceilings, light fixtures, and shelves—then progress downward to walls, furniture, and floors. This ensures falling dust doesn’t ruin already-cleaned spots.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 31: General Cleaning Techniques (Part 2) -->
        <div id="section31" class="section">
            <h2>General Cleaning Techniques</h2>
            <p>3. Clean room by room systematically.</p>
            <p>Tackle one room at a time, starting from the farthest corner and moving toward the exit. This keeps you organized and prevents tracking dirt into finished areas.</p>
            <p>4. Break it down into sections.</p>
            <p>Divide large surfaces (like floors or walls) into manageable chunks. Focus on one section at a time for thoroughness without overwhelm.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 32: Surface-Specific Techniques (Part 1) -->
        <div id="section32" class="section">
            <h2>Surface-Specific Techniques</h2>
            <p>1. Match your method to the material.</p>
            <p>Different surfaces require different approaches:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><i class="fas fa-broom"></i> Hard floors (tile, wood, laminate): Sweep or vacuum, then mop with a cleaner suited to the surface (e.g., pH-neutral for wood).</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-vacuum"></i> Carpets: Vacuum deeply with a powerful machine, then steam clean for stains.</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-window-maximize"></i> Glass/windows: Dust frames first, then use glass cleaner with a lint-free cloth.</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-tools"></i> Metal fixtures: Wipe with a damp cloth and polish if needed.</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-brush"></i> Tile grout: Scrub with a grout brush and a mild cleaner or baking soda paste.</li>
            </ul>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 33: Surface-Specific Techniques (Part 2) -->
        <div id="section33" class="section">
            <h2>Surface-Specific Techniques</h2>
            <p>2. Choose the right cleaning agent.</p>
            <p>Use appropriate cleaners to avoid damage:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><i class="fas fa-spray-can"></i> Glass cleaner for windows/mirrors.</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-tools"></i> Wood polish for wooden surfaces (test first).</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-fire"></i> Degreaser for greasy areas like kitchens.</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-bacteria"></i> Disinfectant for bathrooms.</li>
                <li><i class="fas fa-spray-can"></i> All-purpose cleaner for general surfaces.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>3. Don’t over-wet surfaces.</p>
            <p>Excess water can harm wood or drywall. Use a damp cloth or mop (not dripping) and dry immediately if necessary.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 34: Dust and Debris Removal Techniques (Part 1) -->
        <div id="section34" class="section">
            <h2>Dust and Debris Removal Techniques</h2>
            <p>1. Opt for microfiber cloths.</p>
            <p>Microfiber traps dust without pushing it around. Use dry for dusting, damp for wiping, and rinse or swap them often.</p>
            <p>2. Vacuum smartly with attachments.</p>
            <p>Use a crevice tool for corners and baseboards, and a brush attachment for delicate areas like vents. A HEPA-filter vacuum excels at catching fine dust.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 35: Dust and Debris Removal Techniques (Part 2) -->
        <div id="section35" class="section">
            <h2>Dust and Debris Removal Techniques</h2>
            <p>3. Dust high areas with an extendable tool.</p>
            <p>Use an extendable duster or vacuum wand for ceilings and walls, working in overlapping strokes.</p>
            <p>4. Clear debris in stages.</p>
            <p>Pick up large items (e.g., wood scraps) first, sweep or vacuum smaller bits (like nails), then wipe down surfaces for fine dust.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 36: Efficiency and Workflow Techniques (Part 1) -->
        <div id="section36" class="section">
            <h2>Efficiency and Workflow Techniques</h2>
            <p>1. Try the two-bucket mopping method.</p>
            <p>Use one bucket for clean water and solution, another for dirty water. This keeps your mop effective and floors cleaner.</p>
            <p>2. Overlap your strokes.</p>
            <p>When vacuuming, mopping, or wiping, overlap each pass slightly to avoid missing spots.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 37: Efficiency and Workflow Techniques (Part 2) -->
        <div id="section37" class="section">
            <h2>Efficiency and Workflow Techniques</h2>
            <p>3. Clean in a consistent pattern.</p>
            <p>Move clockwise or counterclockwise around each room to stay systematic and thorough.</p>
            <p>4. Multitask during drying.</p>
            <p>While a floor dries, wipe counters or dust shelves. This maximizes your time.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 38: Safety and Quality Control Techniques -->
        <div id="section38" class="section">
            <h2>Safety and Quality Control Techniques</h2>
            <p>1. Keep the space ventilated.</p>
            <p>Open windows and doors, especially when using chemicals or stirring up dust, to improve air quality.</p>
            <p>2. Inspect with a flashlight.</p>
            <p>Shine a light at an angle across surfaces to spot hidden dust or smudges for a flawless finish.</p>
            <p>3. Do a touch test.</p>
            <p>Run your hand over surfaces—if you feel grit or see residue, keep cleaning.</p>
            <p>4. Take before-and-after photos.</p>
            <p>Photos help you track progress and spot areas needing more work during a final check.</p>
            <button onclick="prevSection()">Back</button>
            <button onclick="nextSection()">Next</button>
        </div>

